defaultCo-ordinated national strategy on resiliencedefault&#xa0;default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe disturbance to seasonal conditions brought about by climate change requires the Government to adopt a strategic approach to dealing with extreme weather conditions. Whilst there has been some progress in this area, we are concerned at the profusion of 
defaultGovernment Departments and agencies that have nominal responsibility for the resilience of the transport network, namely, Department for Transport, Cabinet Office, Highways Agency, Network Rail, 
defaultDEFRA, DCLG and the Met Office.
default The independent rail regulato
defaultr, the ORR also has a significant role, including the monitoring of Network Rail’s budget and performance.
default Responsibility for resilience of the transport network in London has been devolved to Transport for London, and the Welsh Assembly and Transport Scot
defaultland are responsible in Wales and Scotland respectively.
default&#xa0;default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe plethora of organisations with responsibility for resilience of the rail network is symbolic of the wider fragmentation in the rail industry since privatisation and which has gained new momentum
default under the Coalition Government 
defaultas a result 
defaultof the McNulty Review’s proposals to break Network Rail up into regional infrastructure entities
default. The existing fragmentation is a significant barrier to a co-ordinated national strategy for improving the resilien
defaultce of the rail network in the winter months and any further moves toward the regionalisation or breaking up of Network Rail as the national infrastructure management body would ensure that the rail network remains vulnerable to avoidable disruption and del
defaultay in the winter. The Government’s Winter Resilience Review in October 2010
default estimated the ‘welfare cost’ of winter disruption to the transport network to be £280m per day. We believe that this cost would rise if Network Rail is broken up and more responsi
defaultbility for infrastructure management shared with train operating companies through the sort of ‘deep alliance’ that is currently in operation on the Wessex Line between South West Trains and Network Rail.
default&#xa0;default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRMT is also wary of the
default potential impact on rail resilience improvements of the ORR’s proposals
default to allow more open access operators onto the national rail network. This move is supported by the train operating companies as the ORR propose reducing the barriers to open access op
defaulterators of rail passenger services but such a move would add to an already crowded network operators who are subject to less regulation and therefore far less likely to have any interest in investing or working with Network Rail to improve resilience.
